  "prompt": "How often should employees get a performance review?",
  "response": "The frequency of performance reviews can vary significantly based on an organization's culture, size, and specific goals. However, here are some common practices:\n\n1. **Annual Reviews**: Traditional performance reviews are typically conducted once a year. This allows for a comprehensive assessment of employee performance over the year.\n\n2. **Biannual Reviews**: Some organizations opt for performance reviews every six months, providing more frequent feedback and allowing employees to make adjustments throughout the year.\n\n3. **Quarterly Reviews**: More businesses are moving towards quarterly reviews, enabling more regular check-ins that encourage ongoing development and engagement.\n\n4. **Continuous Feedback**: Instead of formal reviews, some companies favor a continuous feedback model, where employees receive informal feedback regularly throughout the year. This approach can help employees make timely improvements and feel more connected to their development.\n\n5. **Project-Based Reviews**: In some cases, performance reviews may be tied to the completion of specific projects, allowing for evaluations to occur as projects are completed.\n\nUltimately, the best frequency will depend on the specific needs of the organization and its employees. It\u2019s essential to find a balance that supports employee development while meeting organizational goals.",
